SIMPLE: jut
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Jut
<hw>Jut</hw> <pr>(j⟦ucr⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Jutted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Jutting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[A corruption of
<ets>jet</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To shoot out or forward; to project beyond the main
body; <as>as, the <ex>jutting</ex> part of a building</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧In <xex>jutting</xex> rock and curved shore.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It seems to <qex>jut</qex> out of the structure of the poem.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To butt.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>jutting</xex> steer.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Mason.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jut</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Jut
<hw>Jut</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which projects or
juts; a projection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A shove; a push.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Udall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jute</ent>⟦br⟧
